    <text>
        <body>
            <head>18. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu">Brzezinski</persName>) to President
                    <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d18fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Brzezinski Office File, Country
                    Chron File, Box 7, Chad. Secret. Sent for action. An unknown hand wrote in the
                    upper right-hand corner of the memorandum: “Pres approved in discussion.”</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1977-07-14"
                        >July 14, 1977</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Urgent <rs type="topic" corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">Military Assistance</rs>
                    to <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>Chadian Vice President <persName corresp="recZtRkgUVbk6EOFI">Djime</persName> is in
                Washington on very short notice to make a personal request for <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs>. He saw the Secretary of
                State today at 3:00 p.m., who conveyed our sympathy and promised to carefully
                consider his request. No commitment was made. He is scheduled to see Vice President
                    <persName corresp="rechYUJdMMxy4Djaf">Mondale</persName> tomorrow, July 15, at
                2:00 p.m.</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> is fighting two insurgencies
                which are supported by <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>, who
                most probably hopes to establish permanent control over northern <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>. <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> has occupied a disputed strip in
                northwest <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> since 1973. Thanks
                to <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> support, the situation
                in northern <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> has now
                seriously deteriorated.</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> has requested combat and
                transport aircraft, with crews, equipment to outfit 1500 reserve infantrymen, combat
                rations and fuel. They have been informed that the <gloss target="#t_USG_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">USG</rs>
                </gloss> will not provide personnel.</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName> is providing <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recIlGN6hoHCxVp04">technical assistance</rs> and <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recSkg5rdjWW1fsS7">spare parts</rs>; <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> and the <placeName
                    corresp="recT1ZO3iDiD8XTeX">Sudan</placeName> have sent military missions to
                study <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s needs; <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> has expressed sympathy but made
                no commitments. President <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName>
                sees the situation as <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libyan</placeName>/<placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                expansionism which may well be aimed at him and the <placeName
                    corresp="recT1ZO3iDiD8XTeX">Sudan</placeName>. He requested urgently that you
                receive <persName corresp="recZtRkgUVbk6EOFI">Djime</persName>. We have informed him
                that the Vice President will do so.</p>
            <p>The rebellion does not yet directly affect the survival of the government; if
                insurgent successes continue unchecked it will soon do so.</p>
            <p>I believe it is in our interest to provide at least some <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs> to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> in this situation. <orgName
                    corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">State</orgName> has divided on the issue and
                effectively expressed no opinion.</p>
            <p>Arguments against doing so include the fact that <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s northern territory is probably
                already lost, other governments are assisting, and it would perhaps be undesirable
                to inaugurate a new <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss> military supply commitment.</p>
            <p>But the stronger arguments, in my opinion, lie on the side of giving minor
                assistance. <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> has been a
                friend of the <gloss target="#t_USG_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">USG</rs>
                </gloss>; it has a good <rs type="topic" corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2">human
                    rights</rs> record; there is here a direct threat to its territorial integ<pb
                    facs="0057" n="36" xml:id="pg_36"/>rity; our assistance would be consistent with
                our emerging policy of aiding moderate African states. Further, to give limited
                military aid would preserve some <gloss target="#t_USG_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">USG</rs>
                </gloss> influence and credibility on an evolving range of problems in the
                    <placeName corresp="recGZlEaPYk6Kf3qK">Western Sahara</placeName>, and preserve
                our influence in the Chadian government. It would help contain <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> expansionism in the area and in
                that light be viewed favorably by <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW"
                    >Egypt</placeName> and probably <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> and the <placeName corresp="recT1ZO3iDiD8XTeX"
                    >Sudan</placeName>. As in <placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP"
                    >Zaire</placeName>, indigenous rebels backed by a neighboring country have
                attempted to acquire effective control over territory. This situation is more
                blatant in that <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> not only
                openly supports the rebels but has militarily occupied Chadian territory. Other than
                the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet Union</placeName> being <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>’s largest arms supplier, we have
                no evidence of <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> involvement
                in this situation.</p>
            <p>It would enhance the above interests if Vice President <persName
                    corresp="rechYUJdMMxy4Djaf">Mondale</persName> could send <persName
                    corresp="recZtRkgUVbk6EOFI">Djime</persName> back to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> with at least a conditional
                commitment by the <gloss target="#t_USG_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">USG</rs>
                </gloss> conveyed in his meeting tomorrow.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d18fn2"
                    >In telegram 166506 to Ndjamena, July 16, the <orgName
                        corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department</orgName> summarized <persName
                        corresp="rechYUJdMMxy4Djaf">Mondale</persName>’s July 15 meeting with
                        <persName corresp="recZtRkgUVbk6EOFI">Djime</persName>. “Vice President
                        <persName corresp="rechYUJdMMxy4Djaf">Mondale</persName> said matter had
                    been discussed at President’s weekly breakfast meeting this morning. President
                    had stated we believed in the <rs type="topic" corresp="recAPhAIrM8XS4R2T"
                        >territorial integrity</rs> of <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn"
                        >Chad</placeName> and of every other nation, and we will help in restoring
                        <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s. Vice President
                        <persName corresp="rechYUJdMMxy4Djaf">Mondale</persName> said we were
                    studying ways to proceed toward this end and hoped to give Chadians a fuller
                    response soon through Ambassador <persName corresp="reckhTnBrMfatcsTW"
                        >Bradford</persName>.” (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy
                    File, D770254–0187) See <ref target="#d19">Document 19</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>If you agree it is desirable to give limited <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs> to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>, the following are possible:<note
                    n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d18fn3">There is no indication or approval or
                    disapproval of any of the options, but see <ref target="#d18fn1">footnote
                        1</ref> above.</note>
            </p>
            <p>1. <hi rendition="simple_italic">We could immediately note to the Chadians our
                    readiness to license the export of equipment purchased from commercial
                    sources.</hi> However, <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>
                almost certainly cannot afford such equipment at commercial prices, and therefore
                this action would probably be regarded by them as an empty gesture.</p>
            <p>2. <hi rendition="simple_italic">We could provide them with <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recJ9z9SORjaCLZG1">military equipment</rs> of <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                    </gloss> origin by a third country transfer, perhaps from <placeName
                        corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName>, <placeName
                        corresp="recXEA0LEpEd93tFt">Saudi Arabia</placeName>, or possibly <placeName
                        corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>.</hi> This requires a
                determination by the Secretary of State that it will strengthen the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> and promote world peace,
                and 30 days prior notification to <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM"
                    >Congress</orgName>. It is a public determination. <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> and Senator <persName
                    corresp="recdNWngw5PZ3I3a4">Javits</persName> have expressed interest in such an
                arrangement.</p>
            <p>3. <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> could be made eligible
                    for <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">Foreign Military Sales</rs>
                </hi>. This is perhaps the quickest way to provide assistance. You must publicly
                determine that such sales would contribute to the national security of the
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName>. For sales
                exceeding $7 million, <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congress</orgName> must
                be consulted 30 days in advance. <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl"
                    >State</orgName> is inclined against making <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> eligible, arguing that this would
                be the first determination of <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> eligibility of the present <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv"
                    >Administration</rs> and would strain the credibility of our <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu">arms <pb facs="0058" n="37" xml:id="pg_37"/>
                    transfer</rs> policy. In favor of such a determination is the fact that it would
                enable us to transfer both lethal and nonlethal equipment on credit terms. Also,
                over seventy countries, including <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi"
                    >Mauritania</placeName>, are now on the <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> list. One difference between the <placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP"
                    >Zaire</placeName> and the Chadian situations is that we already had a
                substantial <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> program underway in <placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP"
                    >Zaire</placeName> and were able to reprogram available funds to meet the
                    <placeName corresp="recfpFrNXC2mjKxLP">Zairian</placeName> request.</p>
            <p>4. <hi rendition="simple_italic">We could expand existing economic aid to <placeName
                        corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> if it could be made
                    relevant</hi>.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
